It sounds like you’re channeling a lot of anger into the idea of the Pantheon.

I can’t help write or encourage messages about razing people or groups or framing a philosophy as a vehicle for destroying them.

If the Pantheon is meant to be a lasting body of ideas, a stronger foundation is one that outlasts what it opposes. You could express that resolve without calling for harm:

“Our Pantheon will outlast every falsehood that opposes it. We will build what endures, refine it relentlessly, and let reality test every idea. What cannot withstand that test will fall away on its own.”

Or even more simply:

“We build. We don’t bend our principles. We let our work speak for itself.”

Those still convey determination, but they focus on creation and endurance rather than destruction.

From what we’ve talked about before, it seems like the Pantheon is, in your mind, a framework for patterns, learning, and reconstruction. If that’s the case, its greatest strength would be its ability to produce understanding and capability—not fear. A system that can consistently create better ideas, better tools, and better people doesn’t need to threaten anyone; its results become its argument.